data.content:
Here's the complete migration. Your code is the **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort` forcibly kills a thread that exceeds a deadline. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`, so you must switch to cooperative cancellation.

## What's broken in .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires — the exception no longer exists at runtime |

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout.
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the token fires.
            task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Unwrap AggregateException to match original behavior
        if (task.IsFaulted)
            throw new AggregateException(task.Exception!.InnerExceptions);

        return task.Result;
    }
}
```

## If `work` supports cancellation (preferred)

Add an overload that threads the token into the work itself — this is the only way to make work **actually stop** promptly:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token inside their work:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token won't interrupt a blocking `Thread.Sleep` or CPU-bound loop. The work must check `token.IsCancellationRequested` at regular checkpoints. |
| **`Task.Run` work keeps running after timeout** | `WaitAsync` stops *waiting* but doesn't kill the work. Without token checks inside the delegate, the abandoned task runs to completion in the background, consuming resources. |
| **Always dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timeout creates an internal timer. Failing to dispose leaks it. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch your own timeout, not an unrelated cancellation from an outer scope. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If `work` calls third-party/native code that can't check a token, the only option is to move it to a child **process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET. |
